auth middleware --> want to create in middleware ? and connect to bootstrap app.php ?? 

No — you do NOT need to create the auth middleware yourself.
Laravel already provides it by default. You only need to use it correctly.

However, depending on your Laravel version (Laravel 11 / 12 changed structure), the configuration location is slightly different. I'll explain both cases clearly.

1️⃣ Laravel 10 and Below

You DO NOT touch bootstrap/app.php.

Middleware is already registered in:

app/Http/Kernel.php

You just use it in routes.

Example

routes/web.php

use App\Http\Controllers\Admin\PostController;

Route::middleware(['auth'])->prefix('admin')->group(function () {
    Route::resource('posts', PostController::class);
});

Laravel automatically uses:

Illuminate\Auth\Middleware\Authenticate
2️⃣ Laravel 11 / Laravel 12 (New Structure)

Laravel removed Kernel.php.

Middleware aliases are defined inside:

bootstrap/app.php

You must ensure auth middleware is registered.

Open:

bootstrap/app.php

Example configuration:

use Illuminate\Foundation\Application;
use Illuminate\Foundation\Configuration\Middleware;
use Illuminate\Foundation\Configuration\Exceptions;

return Application::configure(basePath: dirname(__DIR__))
    ->withRouting(
        web: __DIR__.'/../routes/web.php',
        commands: __DIR__.'/../routes/console.php',
    )

    ->withMiddleware(function (Middleware $middleware) {
        $middleware->alias([
            'auth' => \Illuminate\Auth\Middleware\Authenticate::class,
        ]);
    })

    ->withExceptions(function (Exceptions $exceptions) {
        //
    })->create();

This registers:

auth middleware
3️⃣ Why You Got Route [login] not defined

The auth middleware redirects unauthenticated users to:

route('login')

So your project must have authentication routes.

